Pre-Startup Safety review is conducted. The review is to ensure that the equipment and installation meets design specifications, a Process Hazard Analysis has been completed, employee training has been completed, and safety, operating, maintenance and emergency procedures are in place.

3h. Compliance Audits

Independent compliance audits for processes involving Ammonia and Propane are conducted every three years at a minimum to ensure that the elements of the general accidental release prevention program (forming a part of the site's PSM Program) are up to date and being implemented. An independent auditor and employees having experience and knowledge of the covered processes, and knowledge of the program rquirements conduct the compliance audits. Records of the compliance audit reports are maintained to document the results of the audits and any corrective actions taken.

3i. Incident Investigation

All incidents that resulted in or could have resulted in a release of Ammonia and Propane are investigated promptly. The incident investigation starts with the completion of an Incident Investigation Report prepared by the supervisor on duty at the time of the incident. The report is distributed to the plant Management Team and plant personnel. The Incident Investigation Team is made up of employees having experience and knowledge of the processes affected by the incident, and knwoledge of incident investigations.

Following the incident investigation, a report is prepare to include th following information:

a) date, time, and location of the incident;
b) employee(s) involved in the incident, and their roles;
c) date of the incident investigation;
d) names of the employees on the incident investigation team;
e) description of the incident, including chronology of events;
f) root causes and contributing causes, including conditions at the time of the incident, and;
g) recommendations to prevent recurrence.

Follow-up actions, tat are taken as a result of the recommend

processes to assure that all laws and regulations applicable to its operations and products are known and observed.

The accidental release prevention and emergency response management systems associated specifically with the plant's use on anhydrous Ammonia and Propane involves:

a) The intergration of Safety Management Systems, devices and technologies inherent in the design of the process;
b) Use of Safe Operating Procedures and management practices;
c) Operator training and certification;
d) The ongoing maintenance of plant and equipment;
e) Preperation and testing of site Emergency Response Plan;
f) Maintenance of onsite emergency preparedness, response equipment and a trained Fire Response Team;
g) Coordinating efforts and resources with local emergency response services, and communciating with the community.

2) Description of the Facility and the Regulated Substances Handled:

The IWI Farmers Valley Plant produces fully refined waxes, including food and beverage grade micro-crystalline waxes from various petroleum distillate feed stocks. Feed stocks and products are shipped into and out of the facility via tank trucks and rail cars. The plant has approximately 117 employees and operates 24 hours per day. There are two chemicals at the Farmers Valley plant that are subject to the RMP regulation: anhydrous Ammonia and Propane.

Anhydrous Ammonia is a toxic colorless gas with a strong pungent odor. Ammonia is used as a refrigerant to cool feestock to the Methyl-Ethyl-Ketone (MEK) Unit. The normal maximum inventory of Ammonia is approximately 15,483 pounds.

Propane also is a colorless flammable gas at atmospheric temperature and pressure. It has a vapor density of 1.52 (air = 1). Propane is used as a solvent to remove heavy resins from the vacuum tower bottoms in the Propane De-Asphalting (PDA) Unit. The normal maximum inventory of propane ia approximately 198,080 pounds.

